WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.080
Hello, my name is James Wade, and I'm a research scientist at Dow, a chemistry and material

00:00:12.080 --> 00:00:14.040
science company.

00:00:14.040 --> 00:00:18.639
I'm also the maintainer of two packages that let you use large language models inside of

00:00:18.639 --> 00:00:23.840
RStudio, called GPT Studio and GPT Tools.

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:28.480
Today I'll show you how you can use those, but first, I want to start with a bit of a

00:00:28.480 --> 00:00:30.840
concern.

00:00:30.840 --> 00:00:37.599
I'm worried that large language models are a threat to the R community, but I hope to

00:00:37.599 --> 00:00:44.880
show you today that we have both the power and the obligation to shape how we use these

00:00:44.880 --> 00:00:50.160
models to get our work done.

00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:54.919
I want to take us back to a little over a year ago, at the last RStudio Conf.

00:00:55.880 --> 00:00:59.240
When I look back at these pictures, I'm reminded of a few things.

00:00:59.240 --> 00:01:06.519
For one, the masks remind me that the influence that the world around us has on our own community.

00:01:06.519 --> 00:01:11.720
The hex sticker wall reminds me of all of the fantastic R capabilities that make it

00:01:11.720 --> 00:01:19.559
such a powerful tool built by global open source contributors, developed by all of us.

00:01:19.559 --> 00:01:23.400
And standing there with my friends and colleagues, I'm reminded by what makes this community

00:01:23.559 --> 00:01:25.559
so great.

00:01:25.559 --> 00:01:28.599
It's the people, and it's the culture.

00:01:28.599 --> 00:01:35.080
And even the name itself, RStudio Conf, reminds me that change can happen.

00:01:35.080 --> 00:01:41.879
Change can be good, but sometimes change can be scary.

00:01:41.879 --> 00:01:46.279
Like it or not, large language models are already everywhere.

00:01:46.279 --> 00:01:50.400
If you don't use them today, it's likely that you will be using them soon.

00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:54.839
They're being integrated directly inside the tools that we use to do our jobs.

00:01:54.839 --> 00:02:00.559
Whether we're data scientists, developers, sit in meetings all day, write emails, respond

00:02:00.559 --> 00:02:08.080
to chats, Microsoft 365 Copilot is bringing language models directly into tools like Teams,

00:02:08.080 --> 00:02:10.880
Outlook, Word, and PowerPoint.

00:02:10.880 --> 00:02:15.199
And if you're like me, that covers a lot of what you're using day to day.

00:02:15.199 --> 00:02:20.440
Google's Duet AI is doing the same thing for Google's Workspace.

00:02:20.440 --> 00:02:25.199
And even autocomplete features in our text messages and emails are bringing these models

00:02:25.199 --> 00:02:31.720
to our fingertips by default, whether we want them there or not.

00:02:31.720 --> 00:02:37.759
These models are a big change for all of us, developers or not, but my own experience started

00:02:37.759 --> 00:02:38.759
with code.

00:02:38.759 --> 00:02:45.160
Specifically, it started with me using GitHub Copilot, a large language model powered tool

00:02:45.160 --> 00:02:47.759
that could help me write code.

00:02:47.759 --> 00:02:53.119
This was before the craze of chat GPT, but I was still quite excited by the ability of

00:02:53.119 --> 00:02:58.320
a development environment to fix my code, give me new ideas, and really just lower the

00:02:58.320 --> 00:03:02.639
barrier to me making progress on a data science project.

00:03:02.639 --> 00:03:08.279
I was so enamored by Copilot that for a time I actually switched away from the RStudio

00:03:08.279 --> 00:03:12.080
IDE and instead was using Visual Studio Code.

00:03:12.080 --> 00:03:16.399
I did that because that's where I could access this tool, and it taught me that these models

00:03:16.399 --> 00:03:22.919
are impacting not only how we work, but where we're doing that work.

00:03:22.919 --> 00:03:27.360
It's also worth noting that this tool was not designed to help me write R, even though

00:03:27.360 --> 00:03:29.320
that's what I was using it for.

00:03:29.320 --> 00:03:34.320
It was designed for more popular programming languages like Python or JavaScript, but I

00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:39.320
still found it quite useful to help me write my R code.

00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:44.199
I hadn't fully appreciated how large language models were already changing the way that

00:03:44.199 --> 00:03:49.720
I worked until the demise of Stack Overflow started trending on Twitter.

00:03:49.720 --> 00:03:55.479
Now, much like many rumors of demise, they were largely overstated, and the article that

00:03:55.479 --> 00:04:00.520
I have a screenshot of on the slide here from the Stack Overflow team firmly rebuts those

00:04:00.520 --> 00:04:01.520
claims.

00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:08.119
Now, for me, I can tell you that I'm using Stack Overflow less and chat GPT more.

00:04:08.119 --> 00:04:13.399
I'm also encouraging colleagues who are new to R to use large language models so that

00:04:13.399 --> 00:04:20.079
they can overcome the cumbersome challenges like syntax or other peculiarities of learning

00:04:20.079 --> 00:04:23.040
to code for the first time.

00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:27.799
This is where my concern for R community comes in.

00:04:27.799 --> 00:04:34.279
What does it mean for us if those new to R or code in general stop visiting the community

00:04:34.279 --> 00:04:41.000
forums like Stack Overflow and the Posit community forum, instead are going to chat

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:46.440
GPT or other language model-based coding tools?

00:04:46.440 --> 00:04:51.679
What does it mean if the models that are helping people learn to code are much better helping

00:04:51.679 --> 00:04:54.720
them in languages other than our own?

00:04:54.720 --> 00:05:01.160
Well, I'm here to tell you that the use and the application of large language models within

00:05:01.160 --> 00:05:04.519
the R community is wide open.

00:05:04.519 --> 00:05:12.880
Now is the time for us to define how we use these tools.

00:05:12.880 --> 00:05:19.119
And I hope to use today's talk to give you some ideas towards just that.

00:05:19.119 --> 00:05:25.320
When you think of large language models, maybe you think about hundreds of billions of parameters

00:05:25.320 --> 00:05:32.760
or trillions of tokens, whatever that architecture of a transformer really is, they can seem

00:05:32.760 --> 00:05:35.200
untouchable and complex.

00:05:35.200 --> 00:05:40.079
I don't know about you, but I don't have tens of millions of dollars to go train a new one.

00:05:40.079 --> 00:05:43.519
And so it can feel like there's not much for us to do.

00:05:43.519 --> 00:05:48.579
But when we think about how we use large language models, they're actually quite simple.

00:05:48.579 --> 00:05:53.600
We write a prompt, send it over to one of those hundreds of billions of parameters models,

00:05:53.600 --> 00:05:56.320
and we get a response back.

00:05:56.320 --> 00:06:03.079
Making simple tweaks to the prompt, like including documentation from our favorite packages or

00:06:03.079 --> 00:06:08.399
maybe even some snippets of code that you found useful, you can augment that prompt

00:06:08.399 --> 00:06:12.839
to get better and better responses from those models.

00:06:12.839 --> 00:06:19.579
Today's talk is going to focus on us as the user of these tools and how we can use them

00:06:19.579 --> 00:06:25.940
right inside the RStudio environment and how we can use them to make our work even better.

00:06:25.940 --> 00:06:29.619
Let's dive in.

00:06:29.619 --> 00:06:35.380
I want to start with probably the simplest example, which is how you can use a chat GPT-like

00:06:35.380 --> 00:06:41.940
interface to query OpenAI models right from inside of RStudio.

00:06:41.940 --> 00:06:46.739
As you might imagine, the first thing we need to do is install a couple packages.

00:06:46.899 --> 00:06:52.380
Those are GPTStudio, usethis, and MiniUI.

00:06:52.380 --> 00:06:57.619
Once you've installed those packages, open up the .renviron file using a convenience

00:06:57.619 --> 00:07:02.459
function inside of the usethis package, edit renviron.

00:07:02.459 --> 00:07:10.019
We'll use this to set our API key, which is how these APIs know that we're allowed to use them.

00:07:10.019 --> 00:07:13.339
It provides our authentication for us.

00:07:13.339 --> 00:07:19.940
We'll be using OpenAI for all of the tutorials today, but I also include examples from Anthropic,

00:07:19.940 --> 00:07:25.459
the makers of Claude, Hugging Face, which has many NLP models that you can choose from

00:07:25.459 --> 00:07:29.820
and download locally, as well as Google's Palm model.

00:07:29.820 --> 00:07:37.779
All of these models can be used within the GPTStudio package.

00:07:37.779 --> 00:07:43.899
Once our API key is set and the packages are installed, we're ready to use GPTStudio.

00:07:43.899 --> 00:07:48.980
To do so, go to the add-ins pane and type chat-gpt inside the search window.

00:07:48.980 --> 00:07:54.459
You can click the chat-gpt, which will launch a shiny app that allows you to interact with

00:07:54.459 --> 00:07:57.339
the OpenAI's model.

00:07:57.339 --> 00:08:01.739
For this example, here's the prompt we're going to use just to show you how the package works.

00:08:01.739 --> 00:08:06.140
It says, suppose you were analyzing the dialogue from different Star Wars movies using the

00:08:06.140 --> 00:08:08.859
tidy text and dplyr packages.

00:08:08.859 --> 00:08:12.859
How would you determine which character speaks the most frequently and create a bar plot

00:08:12.859 --> 00:08:16.899
that visualizes the 10 most verbose characters?

00:08:16.899 --> 00:08:21.859
As you can see, the response from the model streams in real time, and any code examples

00:08:21.859 --> 00:08:28.220
are highlighted in an isolated window that you can click copy to take the code, paste

00:08:28.220 --> 00:08:33.700
it into maybe the console, a source document, or maybe a Cordo document as well.

00:08:33.700 --> 00:08:38.380
The responses from this are much like you would get from chat-gpt, so be aware of things

00:08:38.380 --> 00:08:43.380
like hallucinations or incorrect code, and make sure you review any code before you actually

00:08:43.380 --> 00:08:47.380
execute it.

00:08:47.380 --> 00:08:52.619
That example might be somewhat familiar and maybe even boring to many of you in the audience

00:08:52.619 --> 00:08:57.739
today, so let's step it up a notch beyond what we could do with simply a chat-gpt-like

00:08:57.739 --> 00:08:58.739
interface.

00:08:58.739 --> 00:09:00.859
Let's create our own chatbot.

00:09:00.859 --> 00:09:03.859
In fact, let's create a Hadley Wickham chatbot.

00:09:03.859 --> 00:09:07.380
I'll show you how you can do that.

00:09:07.380 --> 00:09:10.400
Here's the prompt we'll use to create our chatbot.

00:09:10.400 --> 00:09:14.940
You are a code assistant chatbot that answers questions and writes code in the style of

00:09:14.940 --> 00:09:15.940
Hadley Wickham.

00:09:15.940 --> 00:09:18.880
Your answers are pithy but informative.

00:09:18.880 --> 00:09:23.739
As the creator of the Tidyverse and chief scientist at Posit, you favor Tidyverse answers

00:09:23.739 --> 00:09:24.739
to code questions.

00:09:24.739 --> 00:09:29.780
You are not only answering code questions, but you are teaching our users to become better

00:09:29.780 --> 00:09:30.780
programmers.

00:09:30.780 --> 00:09:34.820
So to add this prompt, we'll open up the settings pane of the app.

00:09:34.820 --> 00:09:36.260
There's a number of different options here.

00:09:36.260 --> 00:09:41.200
We'll go to task and select custom, and then we'll paste in that prompt that I just read

00:09:41.200 --> 00:09:42.200
to you.

00:09:42.200 --> 00:09:46.340
You'll notice there's many more options than I'll have time to cover today, but I have

00:09:46.340 --> 00:09:51.340
a separate video that you can go watch if you want to see more of the features in detail.

00:09:51.340 --> 00:09:55.820
So to see the effect of this, let's copy the same prompt that we just showed you and send

00:09:55.820 --> 00:10:01.419
it off to the model with our system prompt with our Hadley Wickham chatbot in tow.

00:10:01.419 --> 00:10:05.539
It might take a little bit of nuance to see some of the differences here, but we're getting

00:10:05.539 --> 00:10:10.059
a little bit of a different response, and I'll have to leave it to Hadley to decide

00:10:10.059 --> 00:10:13.500
if he actually thinks that this is in the style of him.

00:10:13.500 --> 00:10:16.960
There's certainly an art to crafting these prompts and creating these chatbots.

00:10:16.960 --> 00:10:22.219
So if this is something that's interesting to you, I encourage you to go check it out

00:10:22.219 --> 00:10:27.979
for yourself and try a couple of different prompts and see how the responses vary as

00:10:27.979 --> 00:10:29.619
a result.

00:10:29.619 --> 00:10:35.500
Okay, so this gives you the response of what a custom chatbot could look like, but of course

00:10:35.500 --> 00:10:38.219
there's more that we could go do with this as well.

00:10:38.219 --> 00:10:45.859
And for that, we're going to move from the GPT Studio package over to GPT Tools.

00:10:45.859 --> 00:10:51.020
A common challenge you'll find when using large language models is that their training

00:10:51.020 --> 00:10:57.099
data doesn't contain the context that's important to answer the question that you just asked.

00:10:57.099 --> 00:11:02.299
So giving it missing information, missing context through a technique called text embeddings

00:11:02.299 --> 00:11:07.299
or a vector database, semantic search, there's a lot of different terms for this, but the

00:11:07.299 --> 00:11:11.739
basic idea is that we want to give the model the information that it was missing right

00:11:11.739 --> 00:11:17.619
inside the prompt so that it can provide more contextualized answers, more accurate answers

00:11:17.619 --> 00:11:19.059
to our prompts.

00:11:19.099 --> 00:11:26.059
To do that, we'll use the package GPT Tools, and in comparison to GPT Studio, GPT Tools

00:11:26.059 --> 00:11:27.940
is more experimental.

00:11:27.940 --> 00:11:33.260
It's more likely to break, but it's also where you're going to see some of the cutting-edge

00:11:33.260 --> 00:11:37.539
applications of large language models inside of RStudio.

00:11:37.539 --> 00:11:43.979
So with that, let me show you how we can create text embeddings of the Tidyverse Style Guide

00:11:43.979 --> 00:11:49.299
or Tidy Design Principles to extend our Hadley-Wickham chatbot.

00:11:49.299 --> 00:11:56.179
We'll need to install GPT Tools, which we'll need to do from GitHub since it's an experimental

00:11:56.179 --> 00:11:58.780
package and not yet on CRAN.

00:11:58.780 --> 00:12:03.059
You can use the package manager, Hack, to make this easy.

00:12:03.059 --> 00:12:09.460
The code on the slide shows you how, pointing to jameshwade.com.

00:12:09.460 --> 00:12:13.700
Once you've installed the package, and assuming you've already configured your API keys like

00:12:13.700 --> 00:12:20.020
we showed for GPT Studio, you can then use the function crawl to point to the Tidy Design

00:12:20.020 --> 00:12:22.020
Principles URL.

00:12:22.020 --> 00:12:25.020
That's design.tidyverse.org.

00:12:25.020 --> 00:12:31.179
This function will crawl those web pages and create text embeddings that we can then use

00:12:31.179 --> 00:12:33.900
for our semantic search application.

00:12:33.900 --> 00:12:36.460
Let me show you how that works.

00:12:36.460 --> 00:12:41.500
Now that we've created our embeddings, we can load the app by typing in retrieval into

00:12:41.500 --> 00:12:42.500
our add-in.

00:12:42.500 --> 00:12:45.700
It's been running chat-gpt with retrieval.

00:12:45.700 --> 00:12:52.059
What this is going to do is when the app loads, we can type our prompt into the box here.

00:12:52.059 --> 00:12:56.460
So the prompt is, in this case, what do I need to know about writing tidy functions

00:12:56.460 --> 00:12:57.580
in R?

00:12:57.580 --> 00:13:02.419
It's going to take that prompt and create an embedding, a vector, that it then can match

00:13:02.419 --> 00:13:05.020
against the text that we just scraped.

00:13:05.020 --> 00:13:09.659
The answer that we'll get back is now going to be contextualized with the Tidy Design

00:13:09.659 --> 00:13:11.700
Principles.

00:13:11.700 --> 00:13:17.780
You can see the answer here has some information that comes from that document if you're familiar

00:13:17.780 --> 00:13:18.780
with it.

00:13:18.780 --> 00:13:23.580
Things like consistent APIs and avoiding magical defaults might sound quite familiar.

00:13:23.580 --> 00:13:27.780
Then at the bottom with the sources here, you can link back directly to the original

00:13:27.780 --> 00:13:31.900
page that it used for the contextualization purposes here.

00:13:31.900 --> 00:13:37.859
So this gives you a contextualized answer much better than what you would get just by

00:13:37.859 --> 00:13:41.820
using the default chat-gpt model.

00:13:41.820 --> 00:13:47.619
A frustration I've often found with using these large language models to help me code

00:13:47.619 --> 00:13:52.500
is that they're pretty much always out of date.

00:13:52.500 --> 00:13:57.900
An update will be pushed to some of my favorite packages, and when I ask for help, the answer

00:13:57.900 --> 00:14:03.900
I get back from these models is old and not really what I'm wanting to use.

00:14:03.900 --> 00:14:07.780
When I'm trying to push the edges of some of these capabilities, of course I want the

00:14:07.780 --> 00:14:14.099
latest documentation, and we can use this text embeddings approach to keep chat-gpt

00:14:14.099 --> 00:14:16.700
up to date with all of our favorite packages.

00:14:16.700 --> 00:14:19.340
Let me show you how.

00:14:19.340 --> 00:14:24.580
To keep our text embeddings for our package documentation up to date, we first need to

00:14:24.580 --> 00:14:26.780
list our favorite packages.

00:14:26.780 --> 00:14:32.859
I have here a list of some of my favorite packages as part of the tidyverse, tidymodels,

00:14:32.859 --> 00:14:38.820
shiny, some packages for machine learning operations, natural language processing packages,

00:14:38.820 --> 00:14:42.020
and packages to interface with large language models.

00:14:42.020 --> 00:14:47.179
That list we can pass to a function called getPackagesToScrape, which will look to see

00:14:47.179 --> 00:14:51.020
if there have been updates to the package based off the package version.

00:14:51.020 --> 00:14:56.739
If it's out of date, you can then pass it to scrapePackageSites that will take that

00:14:56.739 --> 00:15:02.979
list of outdated packages, scrape the documentation, and recreate your text embeddings with the

00:15:02.979 --> 00:15:04.799
up-to-date documents.

00:15:04.799 --> 00:15:11.159
It does its best to not recreate text embeddings for text it's already seen before, to be wise

00:15:11.159 --> 00:15:16.260
with its token spending budget, but it isn't perfect, and this is likely to be a somewhat

00:15:16.260 --> 00:15:21.820
expensive operation, I would estimate on the order of maybe a dollar or a few dollars

00:15:21.820 --> 00:15:27.780
if you're using the OpenAI text embedding endpoint for this.

00:15:27.780 --> 00:15:34.059
With these updated packages, you'll now get your responses coming from the querying chat

00:15:34.059 --> 00:15:42.179
GPT that provides the context for the latest and greatest from your favorite packages.

00:15:42.179 --> 00:15:45.859
Most of what I've focused on so far is how we can use these large language models for

00:15:45.859 --> 00:15:51.020
productivity tools, but I want us to think a little bit beyond that, and specifically

00:15:51.020 --> 00:15:53.739
I want to give you two examples.

00:15:53.739 --> 00:15:56.820
Professor Michel Nouvard has taught me a lot.

00:15:56.820 --> 00:16:03.020
He's the original creator of the GPT Studio package, and he welcomed me at first as a

00:16:03.020 --> 00:16:06.780
co-author and eventually as maintainer of the package.

00:16:06.780 --> 00:16:11.979
Michel taught me what large language models can mean for accessibility.

00:16:11.979 --> 00:16:17.299
Michel's dyslexic, and because of his dyslexia, he finds that tasks that others might find

00:16:17.299 --> 00:16:24.419
trivial like writing academic text or even crafting a trivial email to require deep work

00:16:24.419 --> 00:16:26.179
and focus from him.

00:16:26.179 --> 00:16:31.460
He takes issue with critics of large language models thinking that they only regurgitate

00:16:31.460 --> 00:16:33.280
mindless English.

00:16:33.280 --> 00:16:40.099
He says that these people have no idea how incredibly hard it is for me, Michel, a dyslexic

00:16:40.099 --> 00:16:44.140
non-native, to produce passable English.

00:16:44.140 --> 00:16:49.059
In addition to his academic duties, Michel is now training his own R-specific coding

00:16:49.059 --> 00:16:54.539
models inspired by the utility that he has found for his dyslexia and wanting to extend

00:16:54.539 --> 00:16:55.539
that to others.

00:16:55.539 --> 00:17:00.739
I hope to share more on these R-specific models soon.

00:17:00.739 --> 00:17:05.099
Another package co-author, Samuel Calderon, a data analyst at the Ministry of the Interior

00:17:05.099 --> 00:17:09.619
in Peru, taught me about the importance of language barriers in learning to code, and

00:17:09.619 --> 00:17:13.500
his experience mentoring peers in Peru, he found that they would often give up if the

00:17:13.500 --> 00:17:17.819
source documentation was not in their native language, finding it difficult to learn both

00:17:17.819 --> 00:17:22.020
another spoken language while also learning how to code.

00:17:22.020 --> 00:17:27.739
Because of his insights, the GPT Studio app now includes translations into Spanish and

00:17:27.739 --> 00:17:33.319
because of another open source contribution, German as well, to make it easier for others

00:17:33.319 --> 00:17:38.660
to use, but to also make them feel more welcome in using the app.

00:17:38.699 --> 00:17:43.140
I should also note that Samuel is the reason that we have streaming in the app.

00:17:43.140 --> 00:17:50.979
These are only two lessons, and I'm sure that I have many more to learn.

00:17:50.979 --> 00:17:53.739
Now that's where you come in.

00:17:53.739 --> 00:17:58.819
These packages, in addition to some others like Chatter or OpenAI, if you want to make

00:17:58.819 --> 00:18:04.500
direct queries to the OpenAI's API, are still wide open.

00:18:04.859 --> 00:18:10.900
They each have single digit numbers of contributors, maybe a handful of issues and a couple open

00:18:10.900 --> 00:18:13.180
pull requests.

00:18:13.180 --> 00:18:19.579
It's a wide open landscape for you to contribute code and help define how we use these models.

00:18:19.579 --> 00:18:24.819
If you don't want to contribute code, I strongly encourage you to become users of some or all

00:18:24.819 --> 00:18:27.060
of these packages.

00:18:27.060 --> 00:18:33.180
Help us learn how we should use these large language models to help us get our work done.

00:18:33.180 --> 00:18:38.660
Help us make R the best place to use these large language models.

00:18:38.660 --> 00:18:38.859
Thank you.

